BASF Buys Naphtha in Europe; Gasoil Crack Falls: Oil Products

-- B y   N i d a a   B a k h s h
-- 
2011-05-31T16:54:54Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-31/european-gasoline-rises-gasoil-crack-increases-oil-products.html
BASF SE bought a cargo of naphtha in
northwest  Europe  for $6 more than the May 27 settlement price.
The fuel’s crack, or discount to  Brent crude , widened. Barge
prices of gasoline rose and gasoil futures gained.  Light Products  BASF bought 12,500 metric tons of naphtha from Gunvor
International BV at $987 a ton, priced for delivery to Rotterdam
from June 10 to June 14, according to a survey of traders and
brokers monitoring the Platts trading window, which ends at 4:30
p.m. London time.  Naphtha’s discount to Brent widened to $5.73 a barrel from
$4.82 on May 27, according to PVM Oil Associates Ltd.  Gasoline for immediate loading in Amsterdam-Rotterdam-
Antwerp traded from $1,060 to $1,066 a ton, according to a
survey of traders and brokers monitoring the Argus Bulletin
Board. That’s the highest since May 11 and compares with deals
on May 27 from $1,045 to $1,051 a ton. Gasoline settled at
$1,165 a ton on April 28, according to data compiled by
Bloomberg.  BP Plc and Total SA bought 2,000 tons each of the 7,000
tons that changed hands. Cargill SA was the other buyer. The
trades are for Eurobob grade, to which ethanol is added to make
finished automotive fuel, and are typically for lots of 1,000
tons or 2,000 tons.  Gasoline’s crack increased to $10.50 a barrel from $10.09
on May 27, according to PVM, a crude and products broker in
 London . That’s the widest since May 24.  Middle Distillates  Gasoil futures for June rose 1.9 percent to $960.75 a ton
as of 5:04 p.m. London time on the ICE Futures Europe exchange.
Prices have fallen 7.6 percent this month. The more actively
traded July contract gained 1.7 percent to $962.25 a ton.  Gasoil’s crack, a measure of refining profitability,
increased to $12.60 a barrel at 4:30 p.m. London time, compared
with $11.90 at the same time on May 27, according to ICE data.
That’s the widest since May 11. Brent for July settlement was up
1.6 percent to $116.50 a barrel.  Gasoil barges traded at discounts of $2 and $3 to June ICE
gasoil, according to the survey of Platts.  To contact the reporter on this story:
